body:
This can be fixed pretty easily but we'll lose minimize and maximize animations which make the frameless window appear like a normal window when minimizing and restoring from the taskbar. This functionality was recently merged but https://github.com/atom/atom-shell/issues/751 wasn't closed out. Right now today we can resolve this issue with a fix or resolve the other with a fix but not both.

To get rid of the non-client controls (and border) the following can be done in the NativeWindowViews constructor in native_window_views.cc. We need to remove the window styles from the top level window that are causing the problems.

``` cpp
#if defined(OS_WIN)
  if (!has_frame_ && ui::win::IsAeroGlassEnabled()) {
      HWND hwnd = GetAcceleratedWidget();

      LONG frame_style = ::GetWindowLong(hwnd, GWL_STYLE);
      frame_style &= ~(WS_CAPTION | WS_THICKFRAME | WS_MINIMIZE | WS_MAXIMIZE |
        WS_SYSMENU);
      ::SetWindowLong(hwnd, GWL_STYLE, frame_style);

      // Redraw the frame so the changes take effect.
      ::SetWindowPos(hwnd, NULL, 0,0,0,0, SWP_FRAMECHANGED | SWP_NOMOVE |
        SWP_NOSIZE | SWP_NOZORDER | SWP_NOOWNERZORDER);
  }
#endif
```

There seems to be other more elaborate ways to do it without sacrificing the functionality the window styles give you but I couldn't get it to work. Those ways involve hooking into the WndProc and catching window messages and modifying the default behavior (such as the painting of the non-client area). 

Additionally, I could not figure out how to properly set up the hook to trap the window messages. I spent around 15 hours on it. The main issue was obtaining the proper thread ID for the window. It's not as easy as calling GetWindowThreadProcessId on the window handle. There is more to it from what I can gather. Using Spy++ on the window I can see that a call to GetWindowThreadProcessId infact gives me a different ThreadId than what is reported. I tried EnumWindows as well but was not able to make it work even by looking at all the windows and thread ID's and attempting to match it up. I also tried getting the Module handle to use in setting up the hook instead of the thread ID but that caused all sorts of problems for me.

I'd be really happy if somebody knows how to do this and could show me. There are other areas it may be beneficial to hook into the underlying WndProc to trap window messages (in lieu of the Aura API way which I have not tracked down any documentation on yet).
